description:
Photographed at Poerua River on the Hari Hari Coastal Walkway.
A small member of the Eopsaltriidae family (Australasian Robins) the ngiro ngiro (miromiro in the Noth Island) is a popular denizen of the bush for its habit, like most robins, of seeking people out. 
The bird was nicknamed torotoro (scout) by Maori for its habit of appearing from nowhere in the forest. It was the first to settle on the water troughs with snares attached to them, a scout for the pigeons coming to drink. Then there was its habit of scratching the ground over which an enemy had walked. This was a telltale sign to the warrior looking for footprints of his foe.
In the battle between the land and sea birds in ancient times the Miromiro had a special job too, as torotoro for the land birds, to keep watch on the movements of the enemy. It was considered best suited because of its keen and quick vision, its ability to move rapidly but secretly.
There are several sub-species. The North and South Island sub-species look alike except that the male in the South Island sub species is a lot more yellow in the breast, whereas his North Island cousin is white. Females of both sub species are brown where the male is black and with a creamier, brownish breast.
place_guess: Poerua River estuary, West Coast, New Zealand

tag_list: Canterbury, Arthurs Pass, Petroica macrocephala macrocephala, Petroica, South Island tomtit, tomtit, miromiro
description:
Miromiro - Tomtit - Macrocephala
There are five species of this bird, each restricted to an island and its outlying islands; North Island tomtit, toitoi, South Island tomtit, macrocephala, Chatham Island tomtit, chathamensis, Snares Island tomtit, dannefaerdi, and Auckland Island tomtit, marrineri.

The Miromiro, while tiny in size, played an important role in old Maori rituals, from birth to death. Like the bat, fantail and morepork, appearance of this bird unexpectedly inside a house was regarded as an aitua, omen of misfortune. It was a medium to the gods. The verb “miro” or “mimiro”, perhaps gives a key to the import of the bird’s name, for it means “to twist or twirl rapidly”, “to move quickly”. Its sharp sight in seeking out insects and grubs is recalled in the saying about an observant person, he karu miromiro,a tomtit’s eye. It can spot an insect 10 metres away.
The bird was nicknamed torotoro, or scout by Maori for its habit of appearing from nowhere in the forest. It was the first to settle on the water troughs with snares attached to them, a scout for the pigeons coming to drink. Then there was its habit of scratching the ground over which an enemy had walked. This was a telltale sign to the warrior looking for footprints of his foe.
In the battle between the land and sea birds in ancient times the Miromiro had a special job too, as torotoro for the land birds, to keep watch on the movements of the enemy. It was considered best suited because of its keen and quick vision, its ability to move rapidly but secretly.
In the legend of Maui (Maui–Potiki) who followed his mother Taranga to the underworld, the Matata, Bay of Plenty, version of the myth says that Maui showed himself to the people of the underworld as Miromiro, not as a pigeon. He perched on the crescent-shaped end of a ko, or digging stick, and sang a planting song mentioning his own name and those of his brothers and sisters.
Ever after that event the crescent–shaped part of the ko has been called a whakataumiromiro, and the Miromiro known as “one of Maui’s birds”. Indeed it accompanied Maui to his fatal meeting with the death–dealing Hinenuitepo. Thereafter, Maui manifested himself to man in the form of the Miromiro. It’s voice was Maui’s voice. His spirit lived on in the bird even though his bodily form may have perished.

I set up a backyard mammal trap under a bush and near a fence line front, in the front yard of my flat in the urban area of Lincoln, Canterbury. I set up my trap for several days, which consisted of a tunnel, an ink card for collecting footprints and peanut butter as the bait. 

Luckily, three days later I checked the trap and there were fresh footprints of what looked like belonged to a hedgehog. However, when I finally collected the trap the footprints had been smudged, possibly by another animal, or the same animal trying his luck again. I didn't manage to get a clear photo the first time but these ones might help identify what the animal was with a ruler next to the footprints. There were no additional footprints which confirms that there was only one mammel here.

description: A puteketeke on the nest on the shore of Lake Camp, Ashburton Lakes. Unfortunately in a very vulnerable spot, in a small backwater that is very close to the area where people swim and launch their boats and ride around the shore on their moto-cross bikes. Footprints in the mud show people have been walking right up to the nest. The lowering water levels also means the nest is now attached to the shore making it more vulnerable to land-based predators. This adult was sitting tight, however and had obviously adopted a degree of tolerance to the number of people about. Unfortunately a nest in this location two years ago was smashed by vandals. Here's hoping this one does better.

My husband observed signs of a kiwi 2 years ago on our bush block property. He found this footprint in the mud in a clearing in the bush. He dug out the footprint and we kept it in a tray. He also heard a kiwi call on several occasions in the bush surrounding our house. He compared the call to kiwi calls on the internet and is 100% sure it was a kiwi call. It was very distinctive and different to any of the other bird calls he has ever heard. On one occasion a friend who has observed kiwis in person heard the call too and confirmed it was a kiwi. However, we have not seen any footprints or heard any kiwi-like calls since then. However, we have heard that other people further down the valley on our side of the stream also claim to have heard kiwi. I am not sure if the kiwi that made the footprints and calls that my husband heard is still alive, but I hope it is. Even if it isn't, it must have come from somewhere. Perhaps there is a small isolated population in this valley. If so, I think the kiwis have always been here and survived somehow. The land is quite steep and has a mixture of bush, pine forest and farmland bordering the stream (few hundred acres).

Near the hut below the top of Mt. Takanosu 鷹ノ巣山. In the evening a mother with two cubs came up from slopes of the mountain to the wide wooded ridge  where is the hut. The two cubs looked more shy, while the mother was rather nonchalant  about the presence of a human at close distance (50 meters) and went on browsing the ground. Later in the evening and during the night  many more deer came out around the hut, perhaps a dozen. Judging from the many deer footprints along the hiking path and  the number of trees that have been  covered with metal wire for protection against deer, deer is abundant in the woods and on the ridge of this mountain. A hiker told me that they are very common all the way to Mt. Kumotori 雲取山.  The morning after this sighting, on the bottom of the valley, at Kamozawa 鴨沢, at the start of the hiking path of Mt. Kumotori 雲取山, I spotted  another  couple of this deer.

Mountain lion tracks.

Front track:  Width: 10.2 cm (4"),  Length: 10.2 cm (4")

Rear track:  Width: 8.9 cm (3.5"),  Length: 10.2 cm (4")

Four oval toes register. The leading edge of the metacarpal pad is bilobate; the posterior edge has three lobes, which are very distinct in these photos. The negative space between the toes and metacarpals forms a "C". Nails are not evident in these tracks. Front track is rounder and larger than the rear. 

I could easily follow the tracks for about 100 feet in soft dirt. They were fresh (i.e., not compromised by wind or other footprints). Some of the tracks were on top of horse tracks. There were some deer tracks in this area also. And, surprisingly, very small (2"x2") feline or canine tracks right beside the big ones (4"x4").

A lot has been going on in this area!

Reference:
"Mammal Tracks & Sign" by Mark Elbroch, pp. 206-208.

description:
Lone Cape Barren Goose adult late afternoon on tiny ephemeral beach a few 100 metres north along coastal cliff base's unmade pedestrian track which starts at Roma Mitchell Reserve North Bay Carrickalinga.
Not an ideal photo for ID purposes: the goose is tiny in frame , but sharply outlined against the white sand and its footprints are likewise visible ( it took a few steps towards the sea as it became more anxious the nearer I got.
Smart bird- species now fully protected, almost wiped out due hunting for food within first century of European 'settlement' along with predation by introduced foxes cats etc)
Making a pleasing comeback but no room for complacency.
I looked carefully with binoculars for a mate but was unsuccessful.
However a second goose may have been hidden among the rocks to R of visible bird.
I could not get a closer look in case I disrupted  an attempt at breeding here on mainland shoreline( this species' survival is now largely dependant on breeding on offshore islands but pre-settlement  breeding also occurred on parts of southern Australia's mainland coasts)

description: These tracks were observed in the morning in a large cornfield on a sunny but sub freezing day in which there was little wind after there had been a dusting of snow the previous night. The scale shown in the photos is in centimeters, thus making these footprints most likely belonging to some mouse species.

These tracks were taken on February 13th 2020. The tracks are hard to identify, but evidence suggests they are that of the red fox (Vulpes vulpes). Even thought paw prints cannot be seen. The stride that the animal walks can prove the species. As well as the size of the prints. Which are 2 1/2 inches long by 1 1/2 inches wide. There other animal tracks within the vicinity of the fox’s. There were tracks of the white tailed deer (Odocoileus virginianus) and the eastern cottontail (Sylvilagus floridanus). There was no presence of other humans in the area except for my own footprints(as seen in photos). The temperature at the time was 33 degrees Fahrenheit, with cloud covered sky’s overhead. Along with scattered snow showers throughout the course of the day. Other weather readings such as humidity, wind direction, and daily temperatures can be found in the images provided. Evidence suggests that the red fox came out from the woodland area next to the barn of the Robert A Macoskey Center. Possibly looking for food however, there is no evidence to suggest he found any. Continuing up the hill to the back of the Harmony House. Passing the orchard, and ended near the woodlands bordering Harmony Road.

description: I observed these Red Fox (Vulpes vulpes) tracks on February 9th 2020 at the Macoskey Center. At first, I was questionable that it could possibly be a dog someone was walking down the trail, but without any human footprints in the area, this animal was on its own. The tracks partially followed the Bluebird Trail until veering off into the woods. The tracks measure a bit over 2 inches and are consistent to those of a fox. I can assume that the fox was either headed to it’s home after looking for food, or heading out to hunt. In the area, I was able to identify Eastern Cottontail tracks all over, as well as some I wasn’t able to identify. At the time, it was partially sunny, 39 degrees F, with winds coming from the south at about 8MPH.

description: Hey BackyardBio kids! Sometimes when we go on nature walks, we don't find any critters, but find the signs they leave behind. Things like tracks (footprints), or scat (droppings) give us clues as to what is in our area. Unfortunately, one species tends to leave a lot of stuff behind as well: humans. Sadly we leave all kinds of trash around. While the dragonfly seems to be enjoying this plastic bottle as a perch, trash and pollution can endanger wildlife and can poison our environment. It is fun to watch for signs of what other animals leave behind, as good stewards of our planet, humans should strive to "leave no trace"!

Seen in 7th Brigade park, Chermside, on 25th September 2017; just to the northeast of the Nature's Edge (sic) apartment blocks, which OUGHT to be called "Nature's End", because - in order to protect from fire a 'development' that was allowed to be built right 'on top of' the park boundary with NO buffer/ setback *within* the private-property 'footprint' - the entire "wren thicket" that can be seen in the background of these pictures, and in which 2014-2018 I used to ALWAYS see at least 2 and sometimes 3 or 4 species of wren (fairywrens and the scrub-wren) was "cleared" - totally removed, every leaf and stick, every bit of coarse woody debris, tall grass clumps and shrubs, leaving flat-mown grass in between widely-scattered trees - and all lower branches of those trees were lopped off to above head height. Result: I never see or hear wrens in that part of the park any more.. and there are noticeably fewer about in adjacent areas, I think this must have been a preferred nest site. Brisbane City Council's very successful Wren-and-Other-Small-Woodland-Bird Eradication Programme proceeds apace.

Common Raccoon
•	Trophic level: Primary, secondary consumer
•	Description: The infamous nocturnal bandit. Typically seen only at night, and easily distinguishable by its relatively large size, ringed tail, and black “mask” around the eyes. Bigger and chunkier than an opossum, plumper and probably slower than a fox. 
•	Life Cycle: Breeding begins in mid-winter, with males roaming their range for females to court. Beyond this, males have no role in raising young and move elsewhere to prevent inbreeding. Around two months later, young are born blind and deaf, and do not emerge from the den until several weeks later. Litters are larger in areas with high mortality. 
•	Stage: Difficult to say, based on the fact that these are footprints. But they are about the size the guide gives, so I would guess this was an adult.
•	Sex: Females are a bit smaller than males, but in the field, this would be tough to tell. Obviously, these tracks tell us nothing.
•	Habitat: Deciduous forests and marshes. Require trees to climb and water to forage for invertebrates. I also see them coming in and out of storm drains sometimes. 
•	Predator: On Long Island, virtually none. Birds of prey like Great Horned Owls could pick off young, though. 
•	Prey: Practically anything they can get their hands on. These tracks were found at a saltwater lagoon, and the culprit may eat critters such as Atlantic Blue Crabs.
